WEBVTT

00:06.937 --> 00:09.250
[ Animal howling in distance ]

00:09.285 --> 00:15.256
♪♪

00:15.291 --> 00:19.088
Narrator:
Previously on "Mountain Men"...

00:19.122 --> 00:22.781
Ah, well.Narrator:
Tom rides a run of good fortune.

00:22.815 --> 00:27.337
I'm fixing to make as much money
as what you possibly can

00:27.372 --> 00:30.651
before the trapping season ends.

00:30.685 --> 00:34.517
Narrator: The Hawks close in
on a place to call home...

00:34.551 --> 00:37.244
-What do you think?
-Yes.

00:37.278 --> 00:39.073
...if they can strike a deal.

00:39.108 --> 00:45.148
It's only 10 acres, but 10 acres
means the price is better.

00:45.183 --> 00:47.840
Narrator: And the spring thaw...

00:47.875 --> 00:51.085
Some old tracks here.
It's a grizzly bear.

00:51.120 --> 00:53.777
[ Growls ]Narrator: ...wakes
a deadly threat in Alaska.

00:53.812 --> 00:55.641
Bears are coming out.

00:55.676 --> 01:05.720
We have to be
constantly vigilant.

01:05.720 --> 01:20.563
We have to be
constantly vigilant.

01:20.597 --> 01:22.772
Narrator:
In the depths of winter,

01:22.806 --> 01:24.912
the great Alaska range
is pounded

01:24.946 --> 01:27.328
with as much as 100 inches
of snowfall,

01:27.363 --> 01:31.574
driving the area's wildlife
into hiding.

01:31.608 --> 01:33.507
But once the melt begins,

01:33.541 --> 01:36.751
the forests explode
with activity,

01:36.786 --> 01:38.512
and the largest predators
in the valley

01:38.546 --> 01:41.031
awaken to hunt for
their first meal in months.

01:41.066 --> 01:42.930
[ Growls ]

01:42.964 --> 01:46.692
This time of year, the horses
do get a little more jittery.

01:46.727 --> 01:49.488
When the snow melts,
the bears come out.

01:49.523 --> 01:51.732
Narrator: Morgan's four
Icelandic horses are accustomed

01:51.766 --> 01:54.942
to free grazing the land,
but at this time of year,

01:54.976 --> 01:57.324
with the bear threat
at its most severe,

01:57.358 --> 01:59.878
he pens them in for safety.

01:59.912 --> 02:01.707
Got some bear sign in the area.

02:01.742 --> 02:04.365
Narrator:
And there's just been an escape.

02:04.400 --> 02:06.712
The horses haven't
come back yet.

02:06.747 --> 02:08.645
I gotta get up there
and check on 'em.

02:08.680 --> 02:11.579
Narrator: Icelandics are
workhorses, not sprinters.

02:11.614 --> 02:15.652
They're not capable
of outrunning a bear if chased.

02:15.687 --> 02:17.378
The horses took off
last night,

02:17.413 --> 02:20.450
and we think they went up
to the foothills.

02:20.485 --> 02:22.590
I figured, finish up
the fencing today, too,

02:22.625 --> 02:24.523
so we're better
secured around here.

02:24.558 --> 02:27.906
Thanks.

02:27.940 --> 02:29.632
Be safe.

02:29.666 --> 02:31.772
You, too.

02:31.806 --> 02:34.223
This time of year, they might
not necessarily stick

02:34.257 --> 02:36.846
right to the trail.

02:36.880 --> 02:38.399
They might wander
through the woods,

02:38.434 --> 02:42.023
foraging just between
snow patches.

02:42.058 --> 02:46.407
I'm gonna be looking closely
for any sign.

02:46.442 --> 02:48.271
I'm just hoping I'll spot
their tracks soon and can --

02:48.306 --> 02:50.584
and we'll follow their trail.

02:50.618 --> 03:00.594
♪♪

03:00.628 --> 03:06.703
♪♪

03:06.738 --> 03:09.603
These look like
horse prints here.

03:09.637 --> 03:11.432
Here's a couple more here.

03:11.467 --> 03:17.197
Looks like they joined the trail
coming down this opening here.

03:17.231 --> 03:19.337
I do see some imprints here,
and it looks like

03:19.371 --> 03:21.822
it's probably all four of them.

03:21.856 --> 03:24.480
The horses are definitely
heading up the trail,

03:24.514 --> 03:26.067
so that's the way
I'm gonna head, too.

03:26.102 --> 03:28.518
♪♪

03:28.553 --> 03:32.039
Probably up by the boulders.

03:32.073 --> 03:34.386
They usually get up in the open
where there's more grass,

03:34.421 --> 03:36.216
and they feel more secure.

03:36.250 --> 03:37.527
Holy [bleep].

03:37.562 --> 03:40.081
♪♪

03:40.116 --> 03:42.601
There's fresh grizzly tracks.

03:42.636 --> 03:44.500
♪♪

03:44.534 --> 03:46.916
Here we go.
Boom, boom, boom.

03:46.950 --> 03:51.127
Came off the trail there,
turned onto the trail,

03:51.161 --> 03:53.198
over the top
of the horse's prints.

03:53.233 --> 03:56.857
There he goes up that way.

03:56.891 --> 03:58.030
I don't know if
it's coincidence,

03:58.065 --> 03:59.584
or if he's following
those horses,

03:59.618 --> 04:01.448
but it makes me a little worried

04:01.482 --> 04:04.692
that this bear could have
horse meat on its mind.

04:04.727 --> 04:06.694
I need to get up there
and find them.

04:06.729 --> 04:16.670
♪♪

04:16.704 --> 04:22.503
♪♪

04:22.538 --> 04:25.437
Narrator:
In Montana's Ruby Valley,

04:25.472 --> 04:27.853
calving season is in full swing,

04:27.888 --> 04:29.234
and Rich Lewis is on

04:29.269 --> 04:32.513
to his first promising lead
in more than a week.

04:32.548 --> 04:36.552
Do you smell anything, Capone?
Huh?

04:36.586 --> 04:40.176
The lion went up
the bank right here.

04:40.210 --> 04:42.143
Narrator: He's been patrolling
a local ranch,

04:42.178 --> 04:43.490
trying to track down a lion

04:43.524 --> 04:45.699
that's harassing
the valuable livestock

04:45.733 --> 04:48.184
at the most critical time
of year.

04:48.218 --> 04:49.599
This is real dangerous

04:49.634 --> 04:52.395
'cause the cattle are just
a couple miles west of here.

04:52.430 --> 04:53.741
Hopefully, I can get it
run off of here.

04:53.776 --> 04:56.226
I'm gonna have to go after it.

04:56.261 --> 04:58.332
But I don't know.
It's not real fresh.

04:58.367 --> 05:00.334
Oh, it's kind of blown in here.

05:00.369 --> 05:02.543
Narrator: 4 inches of snowfall
are the breakthrough

05:02.578 --> 05:07.099
he needs to spot lion tracks
and begin the chase.

05:07.134 --> 05:11.172
I just gotta give it a try,
see if the dogs'll take it.

05:11.207 --> 05:14.279
♪♪

05:14.314 --> 05:15.522
-What do you say there, Turbo?
-[ Sniffs ]

05:15.556 --> 05:17.938
Do you smell something, huh?

05:17.972 --> 05:19.457
Wait a minute.

05:19.491 --> 05:21.459
[ Bell clangs ]

05:21.493 --> 05:24.496
I'm gonna start out with Turbo,
Capone, and Diamond.

05:24.531 --> 05:26.360
They've got
a little colder nose.

05:26.395 --> 05:28.362
They can pick up an older scent.

05:28.397 --> 05:33.333
[ Bell clanging ]

05:33.367 --> 05:39.442
Oh, I'm just gonna listen here,
see if they take it or not.

05:39.477 --> 05:41.962
They'll start opening
when they get a good scent,

05:41.996 --> 05:44.792
and it's fresh enough.

05:44.827 --> 05:46.380
Narrator:
The dogs are trained to bark

05:46.415 --> 05:47.519
when they're on a scent

05:47.554 --> 05:51.212
and howl in unison
when they tree a cat.

05:51.247 --> 05:53.767
They're moving it,
going up the mountain.

05:53.801 --> 05:56.666
Gotta keep my fingers crossed
when I hear 'em open.

05:56.701 --> 06:00.118
♪♪

06:00.152 --> 06:03.363
[ Dog howls ]Ooh, there's Capone.

06:07.919 --> 06:09.403
Come on, Capone,
talk to me, buddy.

06:09.438 --> 06:12.130
[ Capone howls in distance ]

06:12.164 --> 06:13.683
Going up that canyon.

06:13.718 --> 06:14.960
[ Dogs howling ]

06:14.995 --> 06:17.273
I'm pretty sure I know
where the dogs are headed,

06:17.307 --> 06:19.171
but they're running so fast,

06:19.206 --> 06:21.415
I gotta get moving
and get caught up to 'em.

06:23.555 --> 06:27.421
I'll try to get closer to 'em
so I can keep hearing 'em.

06:27.456 --> 06:30.390
I gotta hustle down there.
I think I can get 'em cut off.

06:32.702 --> 06:34.428
I want to try to get
as closest to my dogs

06:34.463 --> 06:36.637
as I possibly can,
as fast as I can

06:36.672 --> 06:37.914
'cause I don't want
to take a chance on

06:37.949 --> 06:39.882
losing this lion again.

06:39.916 --> 06:44.438
♪♪

06:44.473 --> 06:46.647
[ Dogs barking in distance ]I can hear the dogs.

06:46.682 --> 06:49.270
♪♪

06:49.305 --> 06:53.516
Just gonna have to go on foot,
get caught up to 'em.

06:53.551 --> 06:54.586
All right.

06:54.621 --> 06:55.794
Let me figure out
what's going on.

06:55.829 --> 06:57.520
I'll get you in the race
there later.

06:57.555 --> 07:01.041
♪♪

07:01.075 --> 07:03.699
Just gonna keep after this cat.

07:03.733 --> 07:05.839
We gotta keep going till
we get it off the ranch.

07:05.873 --> 07:15.849
♪♪

07:18.299 --> 07:20.578
♪♪

07:20.612 --> 07:23.719
Narrator:
In the Ozark Mountains,

07:23.753 --> 07:27.447
the Hawk family has a place
to call home for the first time

07:27.481 --> 07:31.416
since losing their land
seven months ago.

07:31.451 --> 07:35.109
After sticking with it for so
long, we finally found a place.

07:35.144 --> 07:38.147
We have finally
purchased a place.

07:38.181 --> 07:40.149
Narrator: The 10-acre property
has all the qualities

07:40.183 --> 07:42.910
Jason needs,
including fertile soil

07:42.945 --> 07:44.809
and abundant wildlife,

07:44.843 --> 07:48.122
but living here means
starting from scratch.

07:48.157 --> 07:49.538
Come check it out.

07:49.572 --> 07:52.299
Narrator: He's enlisted the help
of an old friend, John Aubrey,

07:52.333 --> 07:55.820
to get the 50-year-old cabin
into working order.

07:55.854 --> 07:59.962
John is a long-standing friend
of the family for years.

07:59.996 --> 08:02.205
He's been doing construction
for a long time.

08:02.240 --> 08:04.380
Check out the inside here.

08:04.414 --> 08:06.555
Uh-huh.

08:06.589 --> 08:09.109
I can do some carpentry,
but I'm not a carpenter,

08:09.143 --> 08:10.386
and I know the difference.

08:10.420 --> 08:12.008
That's one of the reasons
John's here.

08:12.043 --> 08:13.493
The floor's a wreck.

08:13.527 --> 08:16.185
I mean, you can obviously see
why there's no way in hell

08:16.219 --> 08:18.498
I was gonna move anybody
in here until this gets done.

08:18.532 --> 08:22.778
Oh, no, that's, uh...
a little...

08:22.812 --> 08:25.781
[ Wood creaking ]

08:25.815 --> 08:28.128
-A little rotted there.
-A little bit.

08:28.162 --> 08:30.475
The floor is saying,
"Help me, help me."

08:30.510 --> 08:34.686
Well, yeah, these timbers --

08:34.721 --> 08:37.827
they're worse off than
I'd hoped, for sure.

08:37.862 --> 08:39.622
Well, they've been sitting
on the ground.

08:39.657 --> 08:41.141
Yeah.

08:41.175 --> 08:43.384
I think that a lot
of these were rotted

08:43.419 --> 08:45.386
and in not so good shape
when I put 'em in.

08:45.421 --> 08:46.560
Yeah.

08:46.595 --> 08:49.632
We're just gonna have
to tear 'em out.

08:49.667 --> 08:54.603
Well, I say we go ahead
and pull up the boards,

08:54.637 --> 08:59.262
replace what's here, try to
level it out the best we can,

08:59.297 --> 09:00.678
and then put down
new sheeting.

09:00.712 --> 09:03.784
Let's start at this end right
here and just work our way back.

09:03.819 --> 09:06.442
Narrator: The floor is infested
with a wood-destroying fungus

09:06.476 --> 09:08.824
known as dry rot
that can quickly spread

09:08.858 --> 09:11.309
to the rest of the structure.

09:11.343 --> 09:12.966
[ Wood creaks ]

09:13.000 --> 09:14.761
-[ Grunts ]
-Yeah, not so good.

09:14.795 --> 09:18.661
[ Pounding ]

09:18.696 --> 09:20.525
Yep. I think that one's
ready to come out.

09:20.560 --> 09:23.252
I think that one's
ready to come out.

09:23.286 --> 09:26.013
[ Thud ]

09:26.048 --> 09:35.989
[ Wood creaking ]

09:36.023 --> 09:38.543
That do it? There we go.

09:38.578 --> 09:39.751
[ Exhales deeply ]

09:39.786 --> 09:42.892
To be able to get to work
working on my own place

09:42.927 --> 09:45.585
and improve it, that's huge.

09:45.619 --> 09:47.241
♪♪

09:47.276 --> 09:49.865
Narrator: New pressure-treated
lumber is rot-resistant

09:49.899 --> 09:54.110
and should last for
more than 20 years.

09:54.145 --> 09:56.112
You know, right now, we've got
our ply going down,

09:56.147 --> 09:58.183
and it's one heck
of an improvement.

09:58.218 --> 10:00.876
Looking a whole lot better
than it did when we got here.

10:00.910 --> 10:03.016
[ Drilling ]

10:03.050 --> 10:05.639
Well...

10:05.674 --> 10:07.537
I guess it's time to start
tearing this thing down.

10:07.572 --> 10:09.298
Yeah, I guess so.

10:09.332 --> 10:10.989
Narrator: To complete the floor,

10:11.024 --> 10:14.648
Jason and John must remove
an old, decaying shower stall.

10:15.856 --> 10:17.340
[ Wood creaks ]

10:17.375 --> 10:19.273
-Oh, oh, oh!
-We got a snake!

10:19.308 --> 10:22.104
♪♪

10:25.383 --> 10:27.143
O0Narrator:
In the Ozark Mountains...

10:27.178 --> 10:28.697
[ Groans ]

10:28.731 --> 10:30.975
...an unwelcome critter
is already living

10:31.009 --> 10:33.909
in Jason's new homestead.

10:33.943 --> 10:36.325
Jason: Just looks like
a little coral snake.

10:36.359 --> 10:37.913
I'm not messing
with a coral snake.

10:37.947 --> 10:41.917
They're not super aggressive,
but they're super poisonous.

10:41.951 --> 10:44.920
Narrator: Coral snakes have
the most potent neurotoxic venom

10:44.954 --> 10:47.370
in North America.

10:47.405 --> 10:49.683
Jason: But, uh, the coral snake
and the milk snake,

10:49.718 --> 10:52.721
they look very similar
to each other.

10:52.755 --> 10:54.377
What's the old rhyme?

10:54.412 --> 10:57.967
Red and black, venom lack.

10:58.002 --> 11:01.799
Red and yellow kill a fellow.

11:01.833 --> 11:03.939
Looking at this thing
a little bit closer,

11:03.973 --> 11:05.941
it's not a coral snake.

11:05.975 --> 11:07.390
It's a little milk snake.

11:07.425 --> 11:08.909
See where the red
touches the black?

11:08.944 --> 11:10.704
-Mm-hmm.
-It's non-poisonous.

11:10.739 --> 11:12.326
Yeah, you want to go
find him a home?

11:12.361 --> 11:13.707
Yeah.

11:13.742 --> 11:14.743
Let's see if he's got
any more friends out here.

11:14.777 --> 11:16.434
Try to find a sunny rock
somewhere.

11:16.468 --> 11:24.856
[ Saw buzzing ]

11:24.891 --> 11:27.514
There we go.

11:27.548 --> 11:29.585
Got the last pieces of ply in.

11:29.619 --> 11:32.968
I throw in the last few screws
to this thing.[ Whirs ]

11:33.002 --> 11:35.073
We're done.

11:35.108 --> 11:38.145
Yeah, this job came out better
than I thought it was going to.

11:38.180 --> 11:39.733
[ Drill whirs ]

11:39.768 --> 11:44.324
My thing is, is it's gonna make
a suitable shelter for now

11:44.358 --> 11:47.741
that's a lot better
than a tent.

11:47.776 --> 11:51.814
I think that ought about do it.
I sure appreciate it.

11:51.849 --> 11:54.955
Sure, not a problem.

11:54.990 --> 11:56.923
Now it's just time
to tear down the camp.

11:56.957 --> 12:03.619
♪♪

12:07.278 --> 12:09.832
Narrator: In Montana,

12:09.867 --> 12:11.351
Tom Oar is riding high

12:11.385 --> 12:14.388
on his first profitable season
in years --

12:14.423 --> 12:16.770
success that's due in part
to apprentice and friend

12:16.805 --> 12:22.051
Sean McAfee, whose help has
nearly doubled Tom's usual haul.

12:22.086 --> 12:24.122
But productivity on the line
has created

12:24.157 --> 12:28.057
an unexpected shortfall at home.

12:28.092 --> 12:31.095
Tom: I got after the trapping
so hard this winter

12:31.129 --> 12:33.235
that I never even
got to go hunting.

12:33.269 --> 12:35.375
The big game season
came and gone

12:35.409 --> 12:38.274
while I was out setting
and retrieving traps,

12:38.309 --> 12:40.794
so our freezer's empty.

12:40.829 --> 12:43.245
Narrator: 50 miles north
of the Yaak Valley,

12:43.279 --> 12:47.076
bison country is
Tom's best bet to restock.

12:47.111 --> 12:50.977
He's following Sean's lead to
locate the best hunting grounds.

12:51.011 --> 12:52.254
It's later in the winter now,

12:52.288 --> 12:54.118
and most of
the general big game season

12:54.152 --> 12:55.809
is all finished up and tied up.

12:55.844 --> 12:58.847
So one of our best options
right now is a bison hunt.

12:58.881 --> 13:01.332
Coming over here to help him out
on this buffalo hunt's

13:01.366 --> 13:03.955
just one way of me
helping kind of pay Tom back

13:03.990 --> 13:05.405
for all that
he's taught me about trapping

13:05.439 --> 13:08.857
and tanning this winter.

13:08.891 --> 13:12.274
Narrator: One bison can provide
nearly 500 pounds of meat --

13:12.308 --> 13:15.242
enough to last Tom
and Nancy through the summer.

13:20.040 --> 13:23.285
A lot of buffalo sign out here.

13:23.319 --> 13:24.458
Yeah, they sure been here,
huh?

13:24.493 --> 13:26.081
Yeah, they sure been in here.

13:26.115 --> 13:27.737
You can kind of see up
through here

13:27.772 --> 13:29.532
where the animals
have fed through

13:29.567 --> 13:33.847
and pushed that snow back
to get to the grass underneath.

13:33.882 --> 13:35.124
There's buffalo here.

13:35.159 --> 13:38.369
We're just gonna have
to locate 'em again.

13:38.403 --> 13:41.372
Narrator: A bison herd can
travel up to 15 miles a day,

13:41.406 --> 13:45.445
making them difficult to chase.

13:45.479 --> 13:47.171
We can go up over that rise.

13:47.205 --> 13:48.897
A whole nother piece of country
on the other side

13:48.931 --> 13:50.864
of that rise out there.

13:50.899 --> 13:52.486
Yeah.
Hundreds of acres.

13:52.521 --> 13:54.281
-[ Laughs ]
-A lot of ground out here.

13:54.316 --> 13:55.420
Yeah, really.

13:55.455 --> 13:58.182
I've never, ever killed
a bison before.

13:58.216 --> 14:00.184
I've dreamed about it.

14:00.218 --> 14:04.257
The neat thing about the bison
is that they're so big,

14:04.291 --> 14:07.847
you can get a lot of meat
in a very short time.

14:07.881 --> 14:12.921
And if I brain tan the hide,
it'll sell for over $1,000.

14:12.955 --> 14:13.818
-All set?
-Yeah.

14:13.853 --> 14:14.888
I think we got 'er.

14:14.923 --> 14:16.200
All right,
let's go find a buffalo.

14:16.234 --> 14:17.166
-Go find a buffalo?
-Yep.

14:17.201 --> 14:18.581
All right, man.

14:18.616 --> 14:20.549
So, spotting stock is about
the most effective way

14:20.583 --> 14:21.791
to hunt these buffalo,

14:21.826 --> 14:22.931
and you want to be
hunting in ground

14:22.965 --> 14:24.484
where you have a little bit
of topography,

14:24.518 --> 14:26.072
and you can kind of
use the landscape

14:26.106 --> 14:27.901
to put, you know,
ridges and valleys

14:27.936 --> 14:31.180
and coulees between you
and the buffalo.

14:31.215 --> 14:33.873
You see that big old trail
there in the notch there, Tom?

14:33.907 --> 14:35.564
Yeah, I do.

14:35.598 --> 14:38.049
That looks like little
fresher sign, you know.

14:38.084 --> 14:40.189
Yeah.You can just tell by
the way they got that snow

14:40.224 --> 14:41.673
all scuffed up up there.

14:41.708 --> 14:44.055
And they all...All kind of
going over that ridge.

14:44.090 --> 14:45.885
Going over that hill.

14:45.919 --> 14:49.474
-Go have a closer look at it.
-Yeah, I think you're right.

14:49.509 --> 14:51.821
Tom: One of the things that we
have to worry about is,

14:51.856 --> 14:54.721
we're out in the middle
of this prairie,

14:54.755 --> 14:58.207
and buffalo, they say,
can outrun a quarterhorse.

14:58.242 --> 15:01.245
Narrator: Buffalo can run up
to 40 miles an hour and attack

15:01.279 --> 15:05.352
other animals
by ramming at full speed.

15:05.387 --> 15:08.114
So, you can never outrun one,
and there ain't a tree

15:08.148 --> 15:10.461
big enough
to get into out here,

15:10.495 --> 15:13.360
you know, so you just
gotta be paying attention.

15:13.395 --> 15:14.775
Oh, boy, here we go.

15:14.810 --> 15:18.020
Some buffalo right there
on that ridge there, Tom.

15:18.055 --> 15:21.299
Yeah.
There's a bunch of 'em up there.

15:21.334 --> 15:22.507
Yeah, over 20, anyway, huh?

15:22.542 --> 15:24.095
Yeah.

15:24.130 --> 15:26.235
Why don't we stay out
of this wide open stuff

15:26.270 --> 15:28.168
and just kind of scoot
around this ridge?

15:28.203 --> 15:30.032
Around this ridge here,
yeah.

15:30.067 --> 15:32.379
Tom: I've been thinking
about this a lot,

15:32.414 --> 15:36.487
but I don't want to shoot
from 200 yards at the chest.

15:36.521 --> 15:38.661
Then we're gonna be
chasing this sucker all over

15:38.696 --> 15:40.422
and shooting him a second time.

15:40.456 --> 15:44.184
So hopefully,
we can get close enough

15:44.219 --> 15:47.601
to where I can
shoot him in the brain,

15:47.636 --> 15:49.810
and that'll be the end
of it right there.

15:49.845 --> 15:51.709
♪♪

15:54.091 --> 15:57.577
♪♪

15:59.993 --> 16:03.100
Narrator:
In the Great Alaska Range,

16:03.134 --> 16:06.448
surrounded by signs
that the area's grizzly bears

16:06.482 --> 16:08.105
are on the prowl...

16:08.139 --> 16:09.554
Moran: Did have
a little treeline here,

16:09.589 --> 16:12.557
and get a little bit
of a view.

16:12.592 --> 16:14.352
Pull out my binoculars.

16:14.387 --> 16:17.286
Narrator: Morgan's racing to
locate his four missing horses

16:17.321 --> 16:19.840
that have been on the loose
since the dead of night.

16:19.875 --> 16:23.844
Well,
I don't see those horses yet.

16:23.879 --> 16:28.918
I don't see any bears, either.
That's good.

16:28.953 --> 16:31.266
I know their tracks
went to treeline,

16:31.300 --> 16:33.440
so they should
be up here somewhere.

16:33.475 --> 16:36.202
It's just a matter
of how far they've got.

16:36.236 --> 16:38.825
Keep moving and try
to get eyes on them.

16:38.859 --> 16:47.351
♪♪

16:47.385 --> 16:50.871
[ Distant bell rings ]I think I just heard the bell.

16:50.906 --> 16:53.046
It's really faint.[ Bell continues ringing ]

16:53.081 --> 16:57.154
The bells help me hear
where the horses are.

16:57.188 --> 16:59.328
And the bells make a big racket,

16:59.363 --> 17:02.228
so I would hope
that wild animals

17:02.262 --> 17:05.817
would kind of steer clear
of 'em a little bit.

17:05.852 --> 17:07.302
I got a direction on 'em.

17:07.336 --> 17:08.751
[ Bells ringing faintly ]

17:08.786 --> 17:11.996
♪♪

17:12.031 --> 17:15.482
You know, I can hear at least
two bells pretty clearly now.

17:15.517 --> 17:17.933
[ Exhales deeply ]

17:17.967 --> 17:20.073
[ Bells ringing faintly ]

17:20.108 --> 17:25.458
I see one...two, three, four!

17:25.492 --> 17:27.287
Cool.

17:27.322 --> 17:29.255
It's great to see
all four of 'em together.

17:29.289 --> 17:31.705
[ Bell clanging ]Yeah.

17:31.740 --> 17:33.535
Oh, hi there, Lucia.

17:33.569 --> 17:35.571
Feel it.
Yeah, hi, sweetheart.

17:35.606 --> 17:38.022
You doing good up here,
keeping your eyes peeled?

17:38.057 --> 17:39.230
All right.

17:39.265 --> 17:41.094
I'm looking 'em over,
and everyone looks fine.

17:41.129 --> 17:44.925
They seem like they're pretty
relaxed, but pretty watchful.

17:44.960 --> 17:47.963
No sign of the bear up here.

17:47.997 --> 17:50.241
Haven't seen those tracks
since I left the trees.

17:50.276 --> 17:53.002
If this bear was
stalking these horses,

17:53.037 --> 17:56.592
I would find its tracks
circling the area.

17:56.627 --> 17:59.457
Glad to see them all safe.

17:59.492 --> 18:01.459
I'm gonna glass the treeline,

18:01.494 --> 18:04.497
see if any bears
are approaching.

18:04.531 --> 18:05.843
Nice open country up here.

18:05.877 --> 18:08.328
You can see a lot
with a pair of binoculars.

18:10.744 --> 18:14.058
Just keep scanning and looking
and double-check

18:14.093 --> 18:17.993
anything that looks suspicious
and see if it moves.

18:20.168 --> 18:23.826
Haven't seen anything from here.
[ Sighs ]

18:23.861 --> 18:27.140
Cool off. I still don't see
anything up here.

18:27.175 --> 18:29.694
You know, that bear may just
not be coming out of the trees.

18:29.729 --> 18:31.144
Maybe sticking to cover.

18:31.179 --> 18:34.906
I'm gonna head back, try to get
the horses back home safe.

18:34.941 --> 18:38.462
We'll just take it slow,
make our way down the canyon.

18:38.496 --> 18:43.708
♪♪

18:44.502 --> 18:46.849
Narrator:
On Alaska's Glacier Bay,

18:46.884 --> 18:50.059
the turbulent weather moving in
from across the Gulf of Alaska

18:50.094 --> 18:51.958
holds off the coming spring

18:51.992 --> 18:54.547
as ice storms continue
to batter the coastline

18:54.581 --> 18:58.723
where Brent Jameson
is building his homestead.

18:58.758 --> 19:02.037
The weather out here
is extremely temperamental.

19:02.071 --> 19:04.453
It'll go from rain
to snow to clear,

19:04.488 --> 19:06.283
all within the change of a day.

19:06.317 --> 19:08.837
So, I have to take advantage
of every weather window

19:08.871 --> 19:11.909
I can get in order to build.

19:11.943 --> 19:13.911
Narrator: With his permanent
cabin nearly complete

19:13.945 --> 19:15.982
after two months
of construction,

19:16.016 --> 19:18.985
he's determined to finish today
and to spend the night

19:19.019 --> 19:20.952
sheltered from the elements
for the first time

19:20.987 --> 19:24.473
since returning to Alaska.

19:24.508 --> 19:26.268
I've gotta get
my front door done.

19:26.303 --> 19:27.959
That will help seal in the heat,

19:27.994 --> 19:30.790
and I need to build
a wood stove.

19:30.824 --> 19:32.723
This scrap pile over here.

19:34.932 --> 19:37.072
Narrator: He'll use
his remaining scrap lumber

19:37.106 --> 19:41.594
to build a door strong enough
to keep out predators.

19:41.628 --> 19:43.285
I can't use the plywood
by itself

19:43.320 --> 19:45.701
because it's just not
gonna be strong enough.

19:45.736 --> 19:47.565
So I need something
that I can reinforce

19:47.600 --> 19:50.603
to make much stronger
to withstand

19:50.637 --> 19:52.467
a bear trying to get in.

19:52.501 --> 19:54.158
Narrator:
Grizzly bears are five times

19:54.193 --> 19:57.230
stronger than humans
and have jaws so powerful,

19:57.265 --> 19:59.267
they can bite through cast iron.

19:59.301 --> 20:00.923
[ Growls ]

20:00.958 --> 20:02.753
My plan is to
essentially build a frame

20:02.787 --> 20:04.133
on top of a piece of plywood.

20:04.168 --> 20:08.068
[ Pounding ]

20:08.103 --> 20:10.899
♪♪

20:10.933 --> 20:13.108
Then I'm gonna use a piece
of rough cut board

20:13.142 --> 20:15.283
that I milled
from one of the logs

20:15.317 --> 20:17.768
and use that as a support beam
for the door.

20:17.802 --> 20:19.666
It's just a temporary fix.

20:19.701 --> 20:22.151
This should be strong enough
that it would withstand a bear.

20:22.186 --> 20:24.395
For now,
keep it out of the cabin.

20:24.430 --> 20:28.537
♪♪

20:28.572 --> 20:32.058
I am motivated to sleep
somewhere warm and dry tonight.

20:32.092 --> 20:35.199
So, I've got to make this work
one way or another.

20:35.234 --> 20:38.064
♪♪

20:38.098 --> 20:44.381
Got a pretty solid, heavy...
Alaska bush door here.

20:44.415 --> 20:47.315
♪♪

20:47.349 --> 20:49.178
We'll get 'er in there
and see how she looks.

20:49.213 --> 20:53.907
♪♪

20:53.942 --> 20:55.046
[ Grunts ]

20:55.081 --> 21:04.573
♪♪

21:04.608 --> 21:06.644
All right.

21:06.679 --> 21:12.132
Make some minor adjustments
here, she's gonna work.

21:12.167 --> 21:14.100
I'm not building
for luxury here.

21:14.134 --> 21:15.653
I'm building for survival.

21:15.688 --> 21:17.966
I'm really encouraged
to see some light

21:18.000 --> 21:20.348
at the end of the tunnel here.

21:20.382 --> 21:22.867
Getting close.

21:22.902 --> 21:27.734
♪♪

21:27.769 --> 21:34.741
♪♪

21:34.776 --> 21:39.159
Narrator: 6,000 feet up in
the Tobacco Root Mountains,

21:39.194 --> 21:41.369
Rich races to catch up.

21:41.403 --> 21:43.957
It's not easy out here.

21:43.992 --> 21:46.788
This is real rugged country,
a lot of rocks and stuff,

21:46.822 --> 21:50.136
so it's real slow going.

21:50.170 --> 21:52.828
Narrator: His dog team is on
the trail of a mountain lion

21:52.863 --> 21:57.108
that's been menacing a local
ranch during calving season.

21:57.143 --> 21:58.420
I really like to push
the lion away

21:58.455 --> 22:01.181
from a ranch at least 10 miles.

22:01.216 --> 22:04.495
So, I got a long ways to go.

22:04.530 --> 22:08.119
The dogs are quite a ways
in front of me.

22:08.154 --> 22:10.398
When they're on the track,
they open only so often,

22:10.432 --> 22:14.125
so you gotta really listen,
try to get up on high points.

22:14.160 --> 22:17.025
♪♪

22:17.059 --> 22:19.924
Dogs are going right along
the edge of this ridge here.

22:19.959 --> 22:23.549
♪♪

22:23.583 --> 22:26.034
Once they tree,
they're going crazy,

22:26.068 --> 22:28.001
and you can hear 'em
really good.

22:28.036 --> 22:36.147
♪♪

22:36.182 --> 22:39.427
Lion track right there.

22:39.461 --> 22:41.325
That lion probably made a loop,

22:41.360 --> 22:43.948
trying to lose these dogs
in these rocks.

22:43.983 --> 22:46.123
Lions like real rough country.

22:46.157 --> 22:48.608
They don't leave as much scent
on a rock as no snow,

22:48.643 --> 22:52.232
so it slows the dogs down.

22:52.267 --> 22:56.858
They try to pull all kinds
of things to lose those dogs.

22:56.892 --> 22:58.204
They gotta be right up here
somewhere.

22:58.238 --> 23:01.759
♪♪

23:01.794 --> 23:05.349
[ Dogs howling in distance ]

23:05.384 --> 23:07.972
Boy, they're close somewhere.
I can hear 'em.

23:08.007 --> 23:12.598
[ Howling continues ]

23:12.632 --> 23:15.186
There they are. I see a tail.

23:15.221 --> 23:16.429
[ Barking ]

23:16.464 --> 23:18.535
They gotta have that
lion up in that cave.

23:18.569 --> 23:20.709
[ Barking continues ]Holy cow.

23:20.744 --> 23:24.057
[ Barking continues ]

23:24.092 --> 23:27.302
There's a lion in there,
that's for sure.

23:27.336 --> 23:29.304
They're going crazy.

23:29.338 --> 23:32.169
[ Barking and howling continue ]

23:32.203 --> 23:34.309
♪♪

23:34.343 --> 23:36.104
[ Barking in distance ]

23:45.527 --> 23:48.703
O0It's real dangerous
to confront a lion in a cave

23:48.737 --> 23:50.325
because she's got
the upper hand.

23:50.359 --> 23:53.224
You can't move
or get away from her.

23:53.259 --> 23:54.812
The race is shut down
for right now.

23:54.847 --> 23:56.952
I can't jeopardize my dogs,

23:56.987 --> 23:59.783
but this cave is only about
a mile from the cabin.

23:59.817 --> 24:03.234
I need to keep pushing this lion
further off the ranch.

24:03.269 --> 24:04.546
NARRATOR: It's likely the lion

24:04.581 --> 24:07.238
won't come out of the den
until after dark.

24:07.273 --> 24:10.656
♪♪

24:10.690 --> 24:13.072
Usually a mountain lion,
3, 4:00 in the morning,

24:13.106 --> 24:16.489
they start hunting again.
They like to hunt early morning.

24:16.524 --> 24:19.181
But I gotta be able to tell
if the lion came out.

24:19.216 --> 24:21.218
Narrator: An old tracker's trick

24:21.252 --> 24:23.116
will help Rich monitor
the cat overnight.

24:23.151 --> 24:26.188
Rich: My plan is, I'm gonna take
this cedar brush,

24:26.223 --> 24:28.432
block off the entrance
to the cave,

24:28.467 --> 24:32.436
put some branches in the front,
come back tomorrow morning,

24:32.471 --> 24:33.264
and if the brush
is knocked down,

24:33.299 --> 24:35.025
then I know the lion's out.

24:35.059 --> 24:36.751
Then I can put the run
on him again.

24:36.785 --> 24:38.925
♪♪

24:38.960 --> 24:40.133
Looks good.

24:40.168 --> 24:41.514
I got it blocked off.

24:41.549 --> 24:44.517
I'm gonna leave it like it is,
go back to Wilbur.

24:44.552 --> 24:47.762
I'm just gonna spend the night
there so I'm close here.

24:47.796 --> 24:51.144
I can get my dogs right back
on it at first light.

24:51.179 --> 24:54.113
I don't like walking away,
but I don't have any choice.

24:54.147 --> 24:55.701
We're playing cat-and-mouse
right now,

24:55.735 --> 25:00.429
so once she comes out
of the cave, we'll be ready.

25:00.464 --> 25:09.473
♪♪

25:11.233 --> 25:14.305
Narrator:
In the Great Alaska Range,

25:14.340 --> 25:16.376
with the horses secure
at the homestead,

25:16.411 --> 25:20.035
Morgan's patrolling his property
to assess the grizzly threat.

25:20.070 --> 25:22.728
♪♪

25:22.762 --> 25:24.384
Getting into the trees here.

25:24.419 --> 25:30.011
So I got to be extra
watchful and ready.

25:30.045 --> 25:32.807
Some of the stretches
through here are pretty thick.

25:32.841 --> 25:34.878
If a bear was stalking you
and charged you,

25:34.912 --> 25:37.294
you'd have almost
no time to react.

25:37.328 --> 25:43.749
♪♪

25:43.783 --> 25:46.441
Those are today since
the snow softened up,

25:46.475 --> 25:49.582
so they're probably not more
than a couple hours old.

25:49.617 --> 25:51.653
♪♪

25:51.688 --> 25:54.138
It's the same bear.

25:54.173 --> 25:56.347
Narrator: Morgan reconfigures
his rifle sight

25:56.382 --> 26:00.593
to cut down his reaction time
in the event of an encounter.

26:00.628 --> 26:05.287
I got these scope mounts because
they're removable in the field,

26:05.322 --> 26:10.361
and got this little flip-up
ghost ring sight here,

26:10.396 --> 26:13.364
pops into place.

26:13.399 --> 26:14.814
Here, the sights are key

26:14.849 --> 26:18.162
'cause they're so much
faster than the scope.

26:18.197 --> 26:19.681
Narrator: Low-tech iron sights

26:19.716 --> 26:21.580
are a simple
but more reliable way

26:21.614 --> 26:24.513
to quickly line up a shot.

26:24.548 --> 26:28.034
It takes longer for your eye
to focus on a scope

26:28.069 --> 26:30.416
than it does to focus
on the iron sights.

26:30.450 --> 26:32.936
With the iron sights,
I have a better chance

26:32.970 --> 26:34.765
of putting that bullet
into the bear's neck

26:34.800 --> 26:39.459
or skull in a quick way
in these short distances.

26:42.221 --> 26:46.363
Hard to follow a trail
through here.

26:46.397 --> 26:49.055
There's not much in here
that'll show a track.

26:49.090 --> 26:59.031
♪♪

26:59.065 --> 27:01.723
Something's been moving
through here.

27:01.758 --> 27:04.864
♪♪

27:04.899 --> 27:06.555
Hello.

27:06.590 --> 27:09.766
There's some tracks out there.

27:09.800 --> 27:16.082
Did a circle, and it looks like
it headed off across the creek.

27:16.117 --> 27:18.844
It looks like it picked up
a moose trail

27:18.878 --> 27:21.950
and then took off
across the creek.

27:21.985 --> 27:24.090
Hopefully,
it gets a good dinner,

27:24.125 --> 27:26.023
and I can sleep a little easier.

27:26.058 --> 27:28.474
Hopefully, that bear stays
on its side of the creek.

27:28.508 --> 27:30.579
♪♪

27:30.614 --> 27:32.236
Not too long,
the fish'll be running,

27:32.271 --> 27:34.376
and then those bears
will mostly head on down

27:34.411 --> 27:36.862
to get to good salmon streams,

27:36.896 --> 27:38.967
so I think we'll be safe.

27:39.002 --> 27:44.801
♪♪

27:44.835 --> 27:47.320
Oh, hey, Rufus, you been
guarding the yard?

27:47.355 --> 27:48.459
Welcome back.

27:48.494 --> 27:50.841
-Hey, how you doing?
-I'm good.

27:50.876 --> 27:52.429
Well, honey, see any bears?

27:52.463 --> 27:54.949
No. I got the fence
all set back up today.

27:54.983 --> 27:56.364
What'd you see?

27:56.398 --> 27:59.056
Ah, well, looks like it just
walked on the far creek

27:59.091 --> 28:00.851
maybe a half mile away.

28:00.886 --> 28:02.577
It's a good feeling knowing
that the horses

28:02.611 --> 28:05.131
had their excursion
without incident.

28:05.166 --> 28:06.754
It just looks like bears
moving through,

28:06.788 --> 28:09.101
and that's very encouraging.

28:09.135 --> 28:18.524
♪♪

28:21.872 --> 28:23.149
♪♪

28:23.184 --> 28:25.738
Narrator: Across the country
in the Ozarks,

28:25.773 --> 28:28.568
it's moving day
for the Hawk family.

28:28.603 --> 28:31.088
Floors are in,
everything's looking good.

28:31.123 --> 28:35.058
Only thing left for us to do
is pack up, time to move.

28:37.198 --> 28:40.753
Pile of stuff,
big pile of stuff.

28:40.788 --> 28:43.204
That is a pile of stuff.

28:43.238 --> 28:45.378
♪♪

28:45.413 --> 28:51.108
Well, if you want
to grab that side...

28:51.143 --> 28:53.386
I gotta say, it's bittersweet.

28:53.421 --> 28:54.836
Last panel.

28:54.871 --> 28:58.253
You would think that leaving
a tent, you couldn't wait

28:58.288 --> 28:59.841
to get the hell out of there,

28:59.876 --> 29:03.155
but we've made
a lot of memories.

29:03.189 --> 29:05.813
I can guarantee you,
this is a time in River's life

29:05.847 --> 29:07.711
she's never gonna forget.

29:07.746 --> 29:10.541
It's been a long year.

29:10.576 --> 29:13.959
Losing the land we had,
living in a tent for months,

29:13.993 --> 29:16.789
looking for a place to land,

29:16.824 --> 29:23.485
and I'm feeling pretty good
right now, pretty triumphant.

29:23.520 --> 29:27.524
Truck's loaded up.
So, blessings on this place.

29:27.558 --> 29:29.284
It's time to get out of here.

29:29.319 --> 29:34.531
♪♪

29:34.565 --> 29:38.984
I can't believe this is
actually finally happening.

29:39.018 --> 29:42.263
We're finally moving
into a place.

29:42.297 --> 29:43.609
We pulled it off.

29:43.643 --> 29:45.853
It feels real good

29:45.887 --> 29:50.512
just to be getting your own
piece of land.

29:50.547 --> 29:55.586
Just like something
might have shifted back there.

29:55.621 --> 29:56.829
-I'm sure a lot shifted.
-[ Laughs ]

29:56.864 --> 30:00.488
[ Clattering ]Oh, what was that?

30:00.522 --> 30:02.283
We just lost something
off the back.
Yeah.

30:02.317 --> 30:09.428
♪♪

30:09.462 --> 30:11.326
♪

30:11.361 --> 30:13.673
Me and Mary both
kind of looked back,

30:13.708 --> 30:14.847
trying to figure
out what it was.

30:14.882 --> 30:16.987
The camp stove came off
the tail gate,

30:17.022 --> 30:20.473
whole bunch of pipes
out of there.

30:20.508 --> 30:22.234
We don't have a lot
further to go.

30:22.268 --> 30:23.683
Let's find a place
and stuff 'em.

30:23.718 --> 30:24.857
All right, got it.

30:24.892 --> 30:27.826
[ Engine idling ]

30:27.860 --> 30:29.758
Doesn't look like it got
dinged up too bad.

30:33.590 --> 30:35.695
That'll have to do. All right.

30:35.730 --> 30:37.352
[ Engine idling, door creaks ]

30:37.387 --> 30:40.010
I'm glad it's not
a busy highway,

30:40.045 --> 30:42.530
I'm telling you that,
darling.

30:44.946 --> 30:49.917
♪♪

30:49.951 --> 30:51.332
Might want to wake her up.

30:51.366 --> 30:53.058
-River, we're here.
-We're here.

30:53.092 --> 30:55.888
River: Oh, my word!

30:55.923 --> 30:57.752
-Right?
-We are here, ladies.

30:57.786 --> 31:01.031
Whoo-hoo! Ahh.

31:01.066 --> 31:03.102
Look, look, look, look, look.

31:03.137 --> 31:05.967
Come here, come here.

31:06.002 --> 31:08.038
Look at all this.

31:08.073 --> 31:09.246
[ Clapping ]Trees are in bloom.

31:09.281 --> 31:14.527
This is all -- hey, come on.
This is all ours.

31:14.562 --> 31:16.012
You want to know
how you can help?

31:16.046 --> 31:17.151
Uh-huh.

31:17.185 --> 31:18.704
I want you to explore
so you can tell me

31:18.738 --> 31:22.363
where some of the deer trails
and stuff are.

31:22.397 --> 31:25.607
And me and mom are gonna
unload some things, all right?

31:25.642 --> 31:27.264
On your mark, get set, go!

31:27.299 --> 31:30.750
[ Laughs ] Look at her.

31:30.785 --> 31:32.649
Like a fish to water.

31:32.683 --> 31:35.583
Watch your feet for snakes!

31:35.617 --> 31:37.343
She knows.

31:37.378 --> 31:39.345
All right, darling.

31:39.380 --> 31:42.279
♪♪

31:42.314 --> 31:43.971
[ Grunts ]

31:44.005 --> 31:46.421
All right, first item.

31:46.456 --> 31:49.459
This past couple years
has had a lot.

31:49.493 --> 31:51.461
Lost one piece of land,
lost my dad,

31:51.495 --> 31:53.118
lost our assets financially.

31:53.152 --> 31:54.843
And still we came back.

31:54.878 --> 31:57.743
-We're finally here.
-Yes, we are.

31:57.777 --> 31:59.400
It's the simple things.

31:59.434 --> 32:01.367
I'm gonna have some hog
for dinner.

32:01.402 --> 32:03.438
[ Bubbling ]

32:03.473 --> 32:04.888
Can you believe
that we're cooking

32:04.923 --> 32:07.615
in an actual
kitchen surface?

32:07.649 --> 32:10.307
-I know.
-Sink and propane.

32:10.342 --> 32:13.724
It's really nice having
our first meal in this cabin

32:13.759 --> 32:18.557
with a kitchen, stove,
sink that drains.

32:18.591 --> 32:19.834
It's been a long year.

32:19.868 --> 32:24.183
Finally being here,
it feels really good.

32:24.218 --> 32:25.667
Jason:
My little girl and my wife,

32:25.702 --> 32:28.912
to have an opportunity
to see where I came from.

32:28.947 --> 32:30.707
It's been a hell of a journey.

32:30.741 --> 32:33.089
Blessings, blessing,
little family.

32:33.123 --> 32:34.607
Mm. Thank you, thank you.

32:34.642 --> 32:36.126
-Yay-men.
-We're here.

32:36.161 --> 32:38.853
-Yay-men? [ Laughs ]
-Yay-men. [ Laughs ]

32:38.887 --> 32:41.442
[ Laughter ]

32:41.476 --> 32:44.307
-Right, I suppose.
-[ Giggles ]

32:44.341 --> 32:48.759
After a good night's sleep, time
to get moving on this place.

32:48.794 --> 32:52.694
25 years worth of dreams
to make happen.

32:52.729 --> 32:55.214
Best get on it in the morning.

32:58.459 --> 33:05.397
♪♪

33:05.431 --> 33:08.607
Narrator: On Glacier Bay,
Brent is one job away

33:08.641 --> 33:11.023
from his first good
night's sleep in months.

33:11.058 --> 33:14.061
♪♪

33:14.095 --> 33:16.580
It's starting to get dark,
so I have to get into a place

33:16.615 --> 33:17.857
where I can get out
of the weather

33:17.892 --> 33:20.860
and stay warm
and be able to eat.

33:20.895 --> 33:23.449
Narrator: Before he can move
into his new cabin,

33:23.484 --> 33:27.212
he needs a heating system
to make it livable.

33:27.246 --> 33:28.558
Found this barrel out
in the ocean,

33:28.592 --> 33:32.044
and I'm gonna make
her work for my stove.

33:32.079 --> 33:36.290
The idea is to cut an opening
in the front like this,

33:36.324 --> 33:39.362
and then cut a hole
on the top here.

33:39.396 --> 33:41.640
The stovepipe, which I've
already put in the top

33:41.674 --> 33:42.951
of my roof,

33:42.986 --> 33:45.920
will come straight up
the back of this barrel

33:45.954 --> 33:48.095
all the way up to the pipe.

33:48.129 --> 33:49.337
And it'll sit on the ground,

33:49.372 --> 33:52.133
and then I'll be able
to load my wood in here.

33:52.168 --> 33:54.963
Well, let's see how this goes.

33:54.998 --> 33:57.242
Narrator: A chisel and hammer
fill in for a saw

33:57.276 --> 33:59.106
to cut an opening
in the steel drum.

33:59.140 --> 34:06.630
[ Pounding ]

34:06.665 --> 34:09.461
Just cutting little chunks
of the metal out at a time.

34:09.495 --> 34:10.841
It's gonna be a little small,

34:10.876 --> 34:14.397
but I need to keep it
in good shape and make it work.

34:14.431 --> 34:19.712
[ Pounding ]

34:21.818 --> 34:24.372
There's my door flap.

34:24.407 --> 34:25.649
[ Thud ]

34:28.135 --> 34:30.792
Narrator: The hole for
the stove pipe must be precise

34:30.827 --> 34:32.829
to prevent smoke
and carbon monoxide

34:32.863 --> 34:35.487
from leaking into the cabin.

34:35.521 --> 34:37.765
I'm pounding the edges
of this hole back up

34:37.799 --> 34:41.320
because I want the flange
to sit as tightly

34:41.355 --> 34:43.357
as it can
to the metal of the barrel.

34:43.391 --> 34:45.497
That way, no smoke
can escape from the seam

34:45.531 --> 34:47.154
that might be created
between the two.

34:51.192 --> 34:55.023
All right, let's see how
the flange sits on there.

34:55.058 --> 34:56.370
Narrator:
The flange is a metal fitting

34:56.404 --> 34:58.130
that forms an airtight seal

34:58.165 --> 35:01.271
between the barrel
and the stove pipe.

35:01.306 --> 35:02.962
Not too bad.

35:02.997 --> 35:05.827
I think that's gonna
work just fine.

35:05.862 --> 35:09.452
So what I'm gonna do
is screw this baby on.

35:09.486 --> 35:11.868
♪♪

35:11.902 --> 35:13.766
Narrator:
The stove door sits on a hinge

35:13.801 --> 35:17.943
to allow oxygen in
to feed the fire.

35:17.977 --> 35:20.601
So to put the door
back on the barrel,

35:20.635 --> 35:23.051
I'm going to punch
some holes with a nail

35:23.086 --> 35:25.157
and string some trapping wire
through it

35:25.192 --> 35:28.091
and connect the square
that I cut out of the barrel

35:28.126 --> 35:30.266
back to the front of it.

35:30.300 --> 35:34.718
Definitely not gonna be perfect
or pretty, but that's my stove.

35:34.753 --> 35:39.689
Next thing to do is get
a fire started in her.

35:39.723 --> 35:42.864
And burn out all
the residual oil that's inside.

35:42.899 --> 35:44.383
[ Flames whoosh ]

35:44.418 --> 35:46.420
[ Fire crackling ]

35:46.454 --> 35:49.319
Narrator: Burning off any oil
residue removes toxic metals

35:49.354 --> 35:53.358
that could be lethal if released
in an enclosed space.

35:53.392 --> 35:55.739
While the oils burning
out of this barrel,

35:55.774 --> 35:59.916
I'm gonna move all my stuff
from the tent over to the cabin.

35:59.950 --> 36:02.229
Sun's starting to go down,
and it's freezing up again.

36:02.263 --> 36:03.747
I gotta move quick.

36:03.782 --> 36:06.992
♪♪

36:07.026 --> 36:10.720
♪♪

36:13.067 --> 36:14.655
♪♪

36:14.689 --> 36:16.622
Narrator: In eastern Montana,

36:16.657 --> 36:19.349
on the hunt
for some late-winter meat,

36:19.384 --> 36:23.871
Tom and Sean zero in
on a herd of bison.

36:23.905 --> 36:26.356
Hold up, Tom.

36:26.391 --> 36:29.221
♪♪

36:29.256 --> 36:30.912
There they are.

36:30.947 --> 36:35.883
[ Breathing deeply ]

36:35.917 --> 36:40.198
♪♪

36:40.232 --> 36:41.509
These guys are all
coming our way.

36:41.544 --> 36:43.235
They're moving our way.

36:43.270 --> 36:44.374
Now it's kind of the unknown.

36:44.409 --> 36:45.962
Are they gonna bust?
Are they gonna see us?

36:45.996 --> 36:47.653
Are they gonna scent us and run?

36:47.688 --> 36:50.104
If you're ready, we're all
loaded up and ready to go.

36:50.138 --> 36:50.932
Yep.

36:50.967 --> 36:52.796
To walk up on a buffalo herd,

36:52.831 --> 36:56.075
not knowing quite
what they'll do,

36:56.110 --> 36:59.286
it's a strange deal,
real scary, pretty aggressive.

36:59.320 --> 37:01.840
Most of them are not
afraid of people.

37:01.874 --> 37:05.153
They figure they're the boss
here, and their land.

37:05.188 --> 37:07.259
Narrator: Tom and Sean must get
within 40 yards

37:07.294 --> 37:08.881
to get a clean shot.

37:08.916 --> 37:11.090
♪♪

37:11.125 --> 37:12.954
Good bull here, Tom.

37:12.989 --> 37:15.267
Yeah.

37:15.302 --> 37:17.787
Separated from the herd here.

37:17.821 --> 37:20.099
The big one right there.

37:20.134 --> 37:22.757
Narrator: Claiming a young bull
will have the least impact

37:22.792 --> 37:25.243
on the overall population
of the herd.

37:25.277 --> 37:28.211
♪♪

37:28.246 --> 37:31.283
Once they pick their target,
they must act quickly

37:31.318 --> 37:33.665
before the bison sense a threat.

37:36.046 --> 37:37.807
That cow's behind.

37:37.841 --> 37:40.499
This brain is that big around,

37:40.534 --> 37:42.121
and you gotta hit it
with that bullet.

37:42.156 --> 37:45.228
If you go underneath it or over
it, it ain't gonna do nothing.

37:45.263 --> 37:46.885
Here we go right here, mister.

37:46.919 --> 37:48.887
We only got one shot at this,

37:48.921 --> 37:52.684
and if I ruin it,
it could be real dangerous.

37:59.380 --> 38:01.934
O0♪♪

38:01.969 --> 38:05.421
Narrator: Daylight is fading
over Glacier Bay, Alaska,

38:05.455 --> 38:07.526
but Brent is determined
to install

38:07.561 --> 38:10.736
his homemade barrel stove
before nightfall.

38:10.771 --> 38:12.842
If I were to put
the barrel stove on the floor,

38:12.876 --> 38:14.913
the heat from the stove
would burn through the floor

38:14.947 --> 38:17.467
and probably catch
my whole cabin on fire.

38:17.502 --> 38:19.849
So I've gotta have a foundation
for it that's safe,

38:19.883 --> 38:22.369
that's not gonna be flammable.

38:22.403 --> 38:23.749
Narrator: A wood stove
can reach temperatures

38:23.784 --> 38:26.580
of up to 500 degrees.

38:26.614 --> 38:29.997
Properly insulating it from
the wood floor could take days,

38:30.031 --> 38:31.826
but to get out
of the cold tonight,

38:31.861 --> 38:34.208
Brent's devised a quick fix.

38:34.242 --> 38:38.246
Brent: What I'm gonna do is make
a little stand out of the rocks

38:38.281 --> 38:40.248
that I brought
from the fire ring.

38:40.283 --> 38:42.320
Try to get it
as even as possible.

38:42.354 --> 38:45.046
♪♪

38:45.081 --> 38:47.083
All right.

38:47.117 --> 38:49.844
So, now I'm just gonna
connect the stove pipe.

38:49.879 --> 38:54.401
♪♪

38:54.435 --> 38:59.716
Seems to be fitting together
better than I even expected.

38:59.751 --> 39:01.408
Seems to be pretty secure,

39:01.442 --> 39:04.514
but there's only one way
to find out.

39:04.549 --> 39:05.895
And that's to start a fire.

39:05.929 --> 39:10.589
♪♪

39:10.624 --> 39:14.731
Lighting this first fire
in the barrel feels so good.

39:14.766 --> 39:17.976
Not just because it's warm, but
because it represents the fact

39:18.010 --> 39:22.601
that I've accomplished something
that I've worked hard to do.

39:22.636 --> 39:25.639
Despite the troubles,
despite the struggles,

39:25.673 --> 39:28.227
this is definitely worth it.

39:28.262 --> 39:32.128
It's working.
No smoke's coming out the pipe.

39:32.162 --> 39:35.614
Just got a little bit
trickling out here,

39:35.649 --> 39:37.961
but not hardly any at all.

39:37.996 --> 39:40.412
♪♪

39:40.447 --> 39:42.863
Today is a really good day.

39:42.897 --> 39:46.384
I've secured the cabin
that I've dreamed of,

39:46.418 --> 39:48.075
fought through the elements,
fought through the challenges,

39:48.109 --> 39:49.628
and built myself a home.

39:49.663 --> 39:51.250
♪♪

39:51.285 --> 39:54.840
There were a few moments here
that I questioned my ability

39:54.875 --> 39:58.603
to make this happen,
but if I put my mind to it,

39:58.637 --> 40:01.329
I can conquer anything that
this wilderness throws at me.

40:01.364 --> 40:05.126
♪♪

40:05.161 --> 40:08.475
[ Seabirds calling ]

40:08.509 --> 40:12.306
♪♪

40:14.481 --> 40:16.206
♪♪

40:16.241 --> 40:18.795
Narrator: In eastern Montana,

40:18.830 --> 40:22.696
Tom has a 1,200-pound bison
in his sights.

40:22.730 --> 40:24.491
We picked out the bull
that we figured

40:24.525 --> 40:27.148
we wanted
to take out of the herd.

40:27.183 --> 40:30.013
But he's got cows behind him
and all around him.

40:30.048 --> 40:33.603
♪♪

40:33.638 --> 40:36.537
I lost him.

40:36.572 --> 40:38.263
He's on the other side
of the herd now.

40:38.297 --> 40:41.128
[ Sighs ]

40:41.162 --> 40:44.856
-Where's he at?
-Right there.

40:44.890 --> 40:46.340
In the back there?

40:46.374 --> 40:48.238
That one in there
by himself now.

40:48.273 --> 40:49.999
Sean: Here we are out
in the wide open.

40:50.033 --> 40:51.725
We want that shot to be perfect.

40:51.759 --> 40:53.485
If you hit that animal wrong,

40:53.520 --> 40:56.626
then his first reaction
is gonna be to protect the herd,

40:56.661 --> 40:59.491
and that could result
in a charge.

40:59.526 --> 41:00.630
Ooh. Look at that guy.

41:00.665 --> 41:01.700
He's getting
a little aggressive, huh?

41:01.735 --> 41:03.737
Yeah, he's coming right to us.
Here he comes.

41:03.771 --> 41:05.359
He's coming. That's him.

41:05.393 --> 41:07.361
Here he comes, boys.
[Bleep]

41:07.395 --> 41:11.158
We've got no idea how aggressive
this bull is gonna be.

41:11.192 --> 41:14.161
Oh, boy, here we go.

41:14.195 --> 41:17.647
If I don't make a real good
head shot, we're in trouble.

41:17.682 --> 41:27.623
♪♪

41:27.657 --> 41:30.867
Narrator: Next time on the
season finale of "Mountain Men,"

41:30.902 --> 41:33.629
Eustace fights fire with fire.

41:33.663 --> 41:34.906
It's alarming,

41:34.940 --> 41:37.771
a big fire running straight up
into the air,

41:37.805 --> 41:42.085
and those sparks and embers
could fly for hundreds of yards.

41:42.120 --> 41:43.604
Narrator:
The dogs are on the chase.

41:43.639 --> 41:45.192
They got the cat.

41:45.226 --> 41:46.538
Holy cow.

41:46.573 --> 41:47.712
Good job, good job![ Barking ]

41:47.746 --> 41:50.818
Capone, good job, yeah!

41:50.853 --> 41:52.958
He's gonna drop. There he goes.

41:52.993 --> 41:54.822
[ Barking ]I've come this far.

41:54.857 --> 41:56.375
I don't want to lose her now.

41:56.410 --> 41:58.308
Narrator: Marty races to get
out of the red.

41:58.343 --> 42:01.380
This is my last chance.
It has to work.

42:01.415 --> 42:02.968
Narrator:
And Morgan takes aim...

42:03.003 --> 42:05.695
As long as you're far enough
away, and you're a good shot,

42:05.730 --> 42:07.041
it's pretty safe.

42:07.076 --> 42:08.456
Narrator: ...at the future.

42:08.491 --> 42:10.458
Fire in the hole!

42:10.493 --> 42:12.150
[ Explosion ]
